<h2>Geometric Action Model for Robot Policy Learning</h2>
<p>Han et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.17046">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.17046">PDF</a> · <a href="https://cvlab-kaist.github.io/Geometric-Action-Model/">project</a></p>

<p>GAM's central claim is that a pretrained GFM can be the <i>shared substrate</i> for perception, future-state prediction, and action decoding in a manipulation policy. The authors take DA3-Giant (a 40-block DinoV2 <code>vitg</code> trained for metric depth, pose, and multi-view geometry), split it at layer 12, insert a 12-layer causal future predictor, and route predicted future geometry tokens back through the remaining DA3 blocks. A lightweight action head decodes the action chunk; the original DPT depth head decodes future geometry. The result is a single forward pass that predicts both what happens next and what to do about it.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:gam:overview]]</p>

<p>The architecture is more surgical than the abstract implies. Because DA3 blocks 0–12 are frozen and the DPT head is frozen, only ~983 M of the ~1.4 B parameters are trainable: the later DA3 blocks (already pretrained to decode geometry), the 210 M predictor, and the 8 M action head. Our probe against the open Depth-Anything-3 code confirms the backbone parameter split and that layer 13 is the first alternating local/global-attention layer, so the split sits at a natural seam. The first DPT feature layer is 19, which means predicted tokens at the split can still be decoded into future depth maps.</p>

<p>The training objective mixes action regression, future-feature matching, and future-depth supervision:</p>

<p><latex>\mathcal{L}_{\text{total}} = 3\mathcal{L}_{\text{act}} + \mathcal{L}_{\text{feat}} + 3\mathcal{L}_{\text{depth}}</latex></p>

<p>The action and depth terms are weighted 3×; the feature term is weighted 1×. The depth and feature losses anchor the predictor to real geometric transitions; the action loss is standard L1 regression on an 8-step end-effector chunk.</p>

<p>The numbers are mostly consistent with the paper, with one caveat. The open DA3 <code>DPT</code> head is ~35.6 M parameters, whereas GAM reports 50.1 M. The discrepancy is small relative to the total model size but suggests the GAM authors use a variant head or include auxiliary geometry heads. More importantly, the headline 55× speedup over Cosmos-Policy is largely a single-pass-vs-diffusion effect: GAM takes 6.9 ms with CUDA graphs, while Cosmos-Policy takes 382.4 ms. The GFM substrate helps efficiency, but the order-of-magnitude gain comes from avoiding multi-step denoising.</p>

