<p>The camera-robustness claim is the most interesting. On LIBERO-Plus aggregated camera perturbations, GAM reaches ~91% vs. π0.5 ~80% and Cosmos-Policy ~89%. The gain is plausible: depth, scale, and occlusion are explicit in the GFM latent space, so moving the camera perturbs the latent representation less severely than it perturbs pure 2D image features. The real-robot experiments (four tasks, ~200 demos each, external camera shifted 85 cm and 45°) show the same pattern.</p>

<p>What blocks a quick reproduction: the GAM code and the Track4World-tuned DA3-Giant checkpoint are not yet public. The paper also leaves several implementation details implicit—the exact T5 language-encoder variant, the causal-mask shapes in the decoder, and the precise data filtering for the 784K-trajectory pretraining mixture. Pretraining cost is substantial: 64 GH200 GPUs for ~96 hours plus per-benchmark fine-tuning.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>Training VLAs to follow language, not just labels</h1>

<p>Continuous-action VLAs achieve strong in-distribution manipulation, but they frequently collapse to visual shortcuts when language instructions become unseen or compositional. The leading diagnosis is that the action expert starts randomly and is trained on imbalanced VLA data where every trajectory shares one language instruction. This period's strongest response treats action-expert pretraining as the fix.</p>

