<h2>APT: Action Expert Pretraining Improves Instruction Generalization of VLAs</h2>
<p>Xu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.12366">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.12366">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/xukechun/APT">code</a></p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:apt:main]]</p>

<p>APT starts from a Bayesian factorization of the VLA policy:</p>

<p><latex>\pi(a \mid v,\ell) \propto \pi^p(a \mid v)\,\mathcal{L}(\ell \mid v,a)</latex></p>

<p>The first term is a language-agnostic vision-action prior; the second is a language-conditioned likelihood. The paper argues that vision-action pairs are inherently balanced (every frame has its own action), whereas full VLA triplets are language-poor, so pretraining the action expert on vision-action data removes the shortcut incentive before language is introduced.</p>

<p>Our code inspection of the released repository shows this is implemented as a <i>training recipe</i> rather than a separate inference network. In Stage 0 (<code>train_stage=0</code>), only the first N/2 attention layers are built, language tokens are masked out of the causal self-attention, and the VLM is frozen. In Stage 1 (<code>train_stage=1</code>), the stack expands to N interleaved layers: odd-index layers inherit the prior, even-index layers are new mRoPE layers that inject language. The key code path is in <code>VLA.load_from_pretrain(..., load_from_va=True)</code>, which copies each Stage-0 layer i into Stage-1 layer 2i+1.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:apt:architecture]]</p>

<p>Layer-wise gated fusion keeps the prior from being washed out. At every layer the action expert mixes its own vision-language stream with a VLM highway feature through a learnable sigmoid gate:</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="Gated fusion in APT's action expert"><code>vl = vl * sigmoid(w_i) + vl_highway_i * (1 - sigmoid(w_i))</code></pre>

<p>This is exactly the paper's Equation 3. A parameter-count probe on the base config (hidden dim 768, 20 layers) gives 110.45 M parameters in Stage 0 and 193.10 M in Stage 1—the entire growth comes from doubling the attention blocks. The action expert remains tiny next to the Qwen3-VL-2B backbone.</p>

<p>The comparison with neighbors is illuminating. π0.5 protects the VLM with Knowledge Insulation (stop-gradient from action expert) and co-trains on discrete FAST tokens. BayesVLA uses the same factorization but freezes the prior in Stage 2 and relies on a pre/post-contact architecture. APT's move is to keep the prior inside the same weights and jointly finetune it with the likelihood, which the ablations show is enough to make joint VLM tuning helpful rather than harmful. On LIBERO-PRO, π0 and OpenVLA score near 0% under language perturbations; π0.5 recovers on positional shifts but not on unseen task wording; APT substantially outperforms both.</p>

<p>Reproduction is feasible but not cheap. Code and checkpoints are public, but the pretraining mixture spans DROID, AgiBotWorld, InternData, and LIBERO/ALOHA, and training runs at batch size 256 for 100k iterations per stage. The main practical blocker is data collection and GPU hours, not missing weights.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>Interactive world models beyond passive video</h1>

<p>The second half of the drop is crowded with world-model papers, but most are incremental. The one that shipped usable inference code is DreamX-World, which builds a real-time interactive video world on top of Wan2.2. Its value is systems-level integration—camera control, memory, event prompting, autoregressive distillation, and serving optimization—rather than a single new algorithmic primitive.</p>

