<h2>DreamX-World 1.0: A General-Purpose Interactive World Model</h2>
<p>DreamX Team (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.16993">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.16993">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/AMAP-ML/DreamX-World">code</a> · <a href="https://amap-ml.github.io/DreamX_World/">project</a></p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:dreamx:main]]</p>

<p>DreamX-World 1.0 is the latest move in a quickly maturing class of <i>general-domain interactive world models</i> — systems that turn a video generator into an action-conditioned simulator. The landscape has separated into three tiers. Passive text/image-to-video models (Sora, Lumiere, Cosmos Text2World) produce beautiful clips but cannot be steered frame-by-frame. Game-specific interactive engines — GameNGen on DOOM, Oasis on Minecraft, MineWorld, Matrix-Game 3.0 — prove closed-loop rollout is possible in narrow domains. General-domain interactive models — Genie, HY-WorldPlay 1.5, LingBot-World, and now DreamX — aim for photorealistic, game-style, and stylized scenes under user control. DreamX's central bet is that a 5B Wan2.2-based model, plus projective camera conditioning and a stack of training stages, can outperform larger rivals that are already public.</p>

